  "shortBio": "Mossprigs are grove-touched Riftlings of Elderwood Forest, photosynthetic and season-aware. Often mistaken for simple grove beasts, they are gentle companions known for living moss instincts and a quiet talent for reading unstable air. In Elderwood Forest, they favor Groveleaf and soft routines.",
  "standardBio": "Mossprig, titled among keepers as “Thorntrail Trickster,” carries patient growth in every movement. Native to Elderwood Forest, the species unfurls through moss and saplight, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a gentle individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Groveleaf eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Mossprig silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their spatial memory that rivals scout maps makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Moss Needle, reflects a life shaped by Elderwood Forest more than by arena ambition. Many assume Mossprigs are aggressive because of their grove affinity; most are cautious first. Young Mossprigs practice Moss Needle as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Mossprigs first condensed from residual rootwhisper along the living edges of Elderwood Forest after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where moss and saplight gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Mossprig returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Mossprigs as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Mossprig into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Mossprig care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Elderwood Forest still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Mossprigs often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is gentle at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are photosynthetic and season-aware, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through glow-pulses along crest or plates. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as spatial memory that rivals scout maps. They sleep in shallow scrapes and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Mossprigs act as emotional ballast for mixed herds within Elderwood Forest. Allies often include Groveowl and Bramblefox; rivalries with Riftslug and Luminara are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. An old keeper journal swears a Mossprig refused to leave an injured stranger until dawn warmth returned. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Many assume Mossprigs are aggressive because of their grove affinity; most are cautious first. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: Mossprigs can hear micro-fractures in Riftstone as a pressure change behind the ears.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like soft lantern pods veined with grove light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor supportive pulses, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Mossprig is a living chapter of Elderwood Forest. Feed it Groveleaf, respect its gentle tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Mossprig bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
